// The `prelude.json` sub-module: the `json` data type and its conversions. `json` is the tagged
// mirror of a JSON document â€” one `data` constructor per JSON shape, closed into the union synonym
// `json` â€” so a program can traverse an AI's reply with ordinary `match` arms. Referenced from user
// code by the default-import qualifier: type `json.json`, constructor patterns `json.json_object(...)`,
// conversions `json.parse(...)`.
//
// The conversions â€” `json` is an ordinary data type, and every conversion treats it uniformly (no
// special-casing of `json` inside a generic function):
//
//   - `parse : string -> json`         text -> the tree (traverse it with `match`)
//   - `stringify : json -> string`     the tree -> its document text (inverts `parse`)
//   - `encode[T] : T -> json`          embed any value into the tree, by its wire form
//   - `decode[T] : json -> T`          read a tree back as a T, validated against T's schema
//   - `parse_as[T] : string -> T`      fused `decode[T]` of `parse` (no intermediate tree)
//   - `to_text[T] : T -> string`       fused `stringify` of `encode` (no intermediate tree)
//
// Laws: `stringify(parse(t)) == t`; `decode[T](encode(x)) == x` for every T. The value <-> `json`
// conversion is a *total, blind bijection* â€” every value has one unambiguous wire form and back, with
// no schema consulted â€” so the law holds for every T, including a T that contains `json`, an agent, or
// a closure. Validation against T's schema is a *separate* pass layered on top (see the typed readers);
// the codec itself never rewrites a value to fit. The fused pair agrees with the composed one
// (`to_text(x) == stringify(encode(x))`, `parse_as[T](t) == decode[T](parse(t))`). Composing a larger
// document out of existing `json` values â€” a tool list embedding schemas from `get_metadata` â€” is
// explicit tree construction: `json_object(entries = { input_schema = m.input, ... })`.
//
// The typed readers (`parse_as[T]` / `decode[T]`) are schema-directed: the call site's instantiation
// carries T's JSON Schema to the runtime (an inferred instantiation is stamped just like an explicit
// one), the decoded value is validated against it, and a mismatch throws `decode_error` naming the
// offending path. T appears only in the result, so it is never inferable from the arguments â€”
// instantiate explicitly (`json.decode[my_type](...)`); an uninstantiated call is a compile error
// (K3016).
//
// Errors: malformed text throws `parse_error`, a schema mismatch throws `decode_error` â€” ordinary
// `throw` payloads, caught with `use handler { request throw(error: json.parse_error) -> never {
// break ... } }`. (A non-finite number reaching `stringify` / `encode` / `to_text` is a numeric
// invariant violation and panics â€” it has no JSON representation.)
//
// `encode` embeds by wire form: a bare record becomes `json_object` (a key beginning with `$` is
// escaped by doubling it, so it never collides with a discriminator); a `data` value nests its fields
// under `value` â€” `{ $constructor: name, value: { ...fields } }` â€” a disjoint shape a bare record
// cannot forge; an array becomes `json_array`; a `file` its `$ref` handle object; an agent / closure
// its `$agent` / `$closure` reference object (carrying the snapshot / scope it needs to reconstruct).
// A secret operand taints the whole result, which then may not cross a user-facing boundary â€” the
// usual monotonic information-flow rule.

@"A JSON null."
data json_null()
@"A JSON boolean."
data json_boolean(value: boolean)
@"A JSON number without a fractional part."
data json_integer(value: integer)
@"A JSON number."
data json_number(value: number)
@"A JSON string."
data json_string(value: string)
@"A JSON array."
data json_array(items: array[json])
@"A JSON object."
data json_object(entries: record[json])

// A JSON document: exactly one of the seven JSON shapes. (A `type` synonym carries no `@"..."`
// annotation; this comment is its documentation.)
type json = json_null | json_boolean | json_integer | json_number | json_string | json_array | json_object

@"A JSON document failed to parse: the text is not JSON. Thrown by `parse` / `parse_as`."
data parse_error(message: string)

@"A parsed document does not conform to the requested type's schema. Thrown by `decode` /
`parse_as`; `message` names the offending path."
data decode_error(message: string)

@"Parse a JSON document from text into the `json` tree (traverse it with `match`). A malformed
document throws `parse_error`. A number without a fractional part parses as `json_integer`."
primitive agent parse(text: string) -> json with prelude.throw[parse_error]

@"Parse a JSON document from text directly as a T, validated against T's schema â€” the typed text
boundary, with no intermediate `json` tree. Instantiate T explicitly (it appears only in the result,
so it cannot be inferred). A malformed document throws `parse_error`; a schema mismatch throws
`decode_error` naming the offending path."
primitive agent parse_as[T](text: string) -> T with prelude.throw[parse_error | decode_error]

@"Render a `json` tree as its (compact) document text; inverts `parse`. For an arbitrary value,
compose with the embedding: `stringify(value = encode(value = x))`."
primitive agent stringify(value: json) -> string

@"Embed any value into `json` by its wire form: a bare record becomes `json_object`, a `data` value
nests its fields under `value` (`{ $constructor: name, value: { ...fields } }`), arrays `json_array`,
scalars their JSON shape; a `file` becomes its `$ref` handle object, and an agent / closure its
`$agent` / `$closure` reference object. `decode[T]` inverts it for every T (the conversion is total)."
primitive agent encode[T](value: T) -> json

@"Render any value as the (compact) JSON text of its wire form â€” `stringify(value = encode(value =
x))`; the inverse of `parse_as[T]`."
primitive agent to_text[T](value: T) -> string

@"Read a `json` tree back as a T (the total inverse of `encode`: a `$constructor` object re-tags a
`data` value, an `$agent` / `$closure` / `$ref` object reconstructs the callable / file), then
validate the result against T's schema as a separate strict check. Instantiate T explicitly (it
appears only in the result, so it cannot be inferred) â€” `json.decode[unknown]` reads without a
shape. A schema mismatch throws `decode_error` naming the offending path."
primitive agent decode[T](value: json) -> T with prelude.throw[decode_error]

// The tree readers â€” plain Katari over the `json` union, for picking values out of a document of
// unknown or irregular shape (an AI reply, a third-party API response) without a `match` dance at
// every step. The subject parameter is named `target`, uniform with the other container lookups
// (`record.get`, `array.get`). Each reader is TOTAL: a missing key, an out-of-range index or a wrong
// shape yields `json_null()` / `""` rather than an error, so probes chain freely â€” `text(target =
// field(target = element(target = parsed, index = 0), key = "content"))` â€” and absence is checked
// once, at the end, where it matters. For a document whose shape IS known, prefer the typed boundary
// (`parse_as[T]` / `decode[T]`), which validates instead of defaulting.

@"Fold a nullable json read (`record.get` / `array.get`, typed `json | null`) back into `json`:
a missing value becomes `json_null()`. Matching the `null` arm narrows the residual to `json`, so the
fallthrough binds `present` at `json` and returns it unchanged."
agent or_null(value: json | null) -> json {
  match (value) {
    case null -> json_null()
    case present -> present
  }
}

@"The child at object key @key@ (`json_null()` if @target@ is not an object or has no such key)."
agent field(target: json, key: string) -> json {
  match (target) {
    case json_object(entries => entries) -> or_null(value = record.get(target = entries, key = key))
    case _ -> json_null()
  }
}

@"The element at array index @index@ (`json_null()` if @target@ is not an array or @index@ is out of range)."
agent element(target: json, index: integer) -> json {
  match (target) {
    case json_array(items => items) -> or_null(value = array.get(target = items, index = index))
    case _ -> json_null()
  }
}

@"The string @target@ holds (the empty string if it is not a `json_string`)."
agent text(target: json) -> string {
  match (target) {
    case json_string(value => string_value) -> string_value
    case _ -> ""
  }
}
